<body>
  <div class="container">
    <h1>Car Brake System Guide</h1>

    <!-- Purpose Section -->
    <div class="card">
      <h2>Purpose</h2>
      <p>The brake system is a vital safety component of a vehicle, designed to slow down or stop the car when needed. It ensures the driver can control the vehicle's speed and maintain safety on the road.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- Types of Brake Systems Section -->
    <div class="card">
      <h2>Types of Brake Systems</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Disc Brakes:</strong> Use calipers to squeeze brake pads against a rotor to create friction and slow the vehicle.</li>
        <li><strong>Drum Brakes:</strong> Use brake shoes that press outward against a rotating drum to create friction.</li>
        <li><strong>Anti-Lock Braking System (ABS):</strong> Prevents wheel lockup during hard braking, improving control and stability.</li>
        <li><strong>Regenerative Braking:</strong> Used in electric and hybrid vehicles to recover energy during braking.</li>
        <li><strong>Emergency Brakes:</strong> A secondary braking system, often hand-operated, used for parking or emergencies.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <!-- Components Section -->
    <div class="card">
      <h2>Components</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Brake Pads:</strong> Create friction against the rotor to slow down the vehicle.</li>
        <li><strong>Rotors (Discs):</strong> Rotating discs that the brake pads clamp onto to create friction.</li>
        <li><strong>Calipers:</strong> House the brake pads and apply pressure to the rotor.</li>
        <li><strong>Brake Lines:</strong> Carry brake fluid from the master cylinder to the brakes.</li>
        <li><strong>Master Cylinder:</strong> Converts the force from the brake pedal into hydraulic pressure.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <!-- Maintenance Section -->
    <div class="card">
      <h2>Maintenance</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Regularly inspect brake pads and rotors for wear and replace them if necessary.</li>
        <li>Check brake fluid levels and top up or replace the fluid as needed.</li>
        <li>Inspect brake lines for leaks or damage and repair them promptly.</li>
        <li>Listen for unusual noises (e.g., squeaking or grinding) that may indicate brake issues.</li>
        <li>Test the brake system regularly to ensure it is functioning properly.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <!-- Signs of Brake Issues Section -->
    <div class="card">
      <h2>Signs of Brake Issues</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Squeaking or Grinding Noises:</strong> Indicates worn brake pads or rotors.</li>
        <li><strong>Vibrations:</strong> Shaking or pulsating brake pedal or steering wheel during braking.</li>
        <li><strong>Soft Brake Pedal:</strong> A spongy or sinking brake pedal may indicate air in the brake lines or a fluid leak.</li>
        <li><strong>Pulling to One Side:</strong> The vehicle pulls to one side when braking, indicating uneven brake wear or a stuck caliper.</li>
        <li><strong>Warning Lights:</strong> The brake warning light or ABS light on the dashboard may indicate a problem.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

